---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import Term from "../../components/Term.astro";
import buggy from "../../../derived/filter/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/filter/procedural.trace.json";
import clever from "../../../derived/filter/clever.trace.json";

// Buggy first: deleting-while-looping skips an element, then the safe build-a-new-list way, then a comprehension.
const registers = [buggy, procedural, clever];
---

<Base
  title="Filtering a list — GlassBox"
  description="Keep the items that pass a test — and watch why deleting from a list while looping over it skips elements."
>
  <LessonNav slug="filter" position="top" />

  <h1>Filtering a list</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Filtering — keeping only the items that pass some test — is the everyday move behind "find the data
    that matters." The safe way is to build a <em>new</em> <Term s="list">list</Term>. The tempting way is to delete the
    unwanted items in place, and the state pane shows exactly why that backfires.
  </p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>
      The list is <code>[4, 3, 22, 18, 7, 15]</code> and we want only the numbers over 10. The right
      answer is <code>[22, 18, 15]</code>.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Buggy</strong> — deletes each small number from <code>nums</code> while looping over it.
        Removing <code>4</code> shifts <code>3</code> into a slot the <Term s="loop">loop</Term> has already passed, so <code>3</code> is skipped and survives. <code>nums</code> ends as <code>[3, 22, 18, 15]</code> — a small number leaked through, and the original list is destroyed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Procedural</strong> — copies the passing numbers into a fresh list <code>big</code> and
        never touches <code>nums</code>. Nothing shifts under the loop, so nothing is skipped.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Compact</strong> — <code>[n for n in nums if n &gt; 10]</code> builds the new list in one
        expression. Python still runs it as a loop — watch <code>n</code> take each <Term s="value">value</Term> — and
        <code>big</code> appears complete at the end.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">
      Every state you see came from running the program under CPython's tracer at build time — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
  <LessonNav slug="filter" position="bottom" />
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
